AGI - The Minister for Culture of Israel, Miki Zohar, denounces the victory at the Oscars of the Palestinian-Israeli documentary <a href="https://www.agi.it/show/news/2024-11-15/medfilm-festival-five-premi-a-lungometraggio-no-other-land-28738890/">"No Other Land"<ce l' Israel because "
&nbsp;
Zohar's "J'accuse" came with a message about X, a few hours after the triumph in Los Angeles of the film that documents the demolitions made by Israel in the Palestinian village of Masafer Yatta, in the West Bank.
<div </div
"The Oscar's victory for the film 'No Other Land' is a sad moment for the cinema world - instead of presenting the complexity of our reality, the directors chose to echo narrations that distort the image of Israel in the world," wrote Zohar on X. "Freedom of expression is an important value, but transforming Israel's slander into an instrument of international promotion is not creativity - it is sabotage of the State of Israel, and after the massacre of 7 October and the ongoing war, it does doublely harm," the Israeli minister stressed.
&nbsp;
Zohar states that victory demonstrates the need for legislation "to ensure that public resources are directed to works that speak to the Israeli public, and not to an industry that makes a career by defamating the country in foreign festivals".
&nbsp;
Zohar also supported the need for reform to push government funds towards commercial films rather than artistic films and documentaries that shed light on the periphery and Israeli minorities, thus giving more funding to films based on the number of spectators and ticket sales. His proposal is seen by film professionals as an effort by the Israeli right-wing government to silence liberal voices and limit opportunities to voice untraditional and unfair perspectives. &nbsp;
