AGI -&nbsp; US duties on Canadian and Mexican goods entered into force. The deadline has passed without an agreement.<br> Canadian goods will be subject to a duty of 25% >- with energy resources affected by a lower rate of 10% - while Mexican products will be subject to a generalized taxation of 25%, according to the orders previously signed by Trump. The US President mentioned the lack of progress in the fight against drug trafficking to push duties.
Beijing has announced that it will impose additional tariffs > on a series of US products, including chicken, wheat, corn and soy, > in response to the new US taxes on Chinese goods. "Agendo unilaterally, Washington is undermining the multilateral trading system" and "indebteding the foundations of economic and commercial cooperation between China and the United States," said the Chinese Ministry of Commerce in a statement.
Trump also signed an order to further increase i&nbsp;dazi&nbsp; on imports from China. It makes known the White House that criticizes "the inability" of Beijing to face the illegal trade of fentanyl. >The new measure doubles to 20% the tariff for goods from China. As for Mexico and Canada, "there is no more possibilities" that can avoid new tariffs, Trump said during a press conference on foreign investments in the USA.&nbsp;
Already today, except for the last hour's route changes, the new US duties for Mexico and Canada could be fixed, which are currently expected to 25%. Needless to say that a new tariff imposition would have a strong impact on different U.S. industrial sectors, beginning with the highly integrated automotive industry. The U.S. car brands, in fact, often count, if not on the whole assembly, surely on different components of Mexico e&nbsp;Canada.> Starting with the same Tesla of Elon Musk, which builds its models at national level entirely in the United States but for these cars include about 20% of parts and components from Mexico.
The duties at 25% would make cars even more expensive in the United States, which are already high after the impennata recorded during the pandemic. Since 2019, in fact, the average cost of approximately 44,000 dollars has increased by 25%. Increases in customs tariffs on&nbsp;Canada&nbsp; and Mexico would mean an average increase in costs of $3,125 per vehicle, based on an analysis of JP Morgan reported by the Wall Street Journal. It is not yet clear, however, according to the Wsj, what share of those additional costs would be absorbed by car manufacturers and their suppliers. Moreover, it is still clear that the administration will provide exemptions for cars that comply with the US-Mexico-Canada&nbsp free trade agreement; (Usmca) wanted by Trump.
The Financial Times cites the case of the&nbsp;Chevrolet Silverado, one of America's most popular pick-ups since it was launched in 1998.&nbsp; The iconic vehicle could become one of the victims of the commercial war that are about to open the United States with new duties. The model of the General Motors, which costs between 40,000 and 70,000 dollars, is based on a complex automotive chain, which makes it particularly vulnerable to the threat of imposing duty &nbsp; 25% on Canada and Mexico. Of the 673,000 Silverado products last year, 31% was built in GM plant in the Mexican city of Silao and 20% in the plant in Oshawa, Canada. But even for about half of the vehicles produced in three American plants in Michigan and Indiana, it is likely that the servosterzo and door panels are built in Mexico, back lighting in Canada, the airbag module in Germany and the central console display in Japan, according to S&amp;P&nbsp;Global&nbsp;Mobility data. GM is preparing for the &nbsp duties; since Trump's election, financial director Paul Jacobson declared during a conference with investors last month. The automaker, remembers the Ft, moved part of the production and reduced almost a third the stocks in the plants outside the United States. If tariffs become permanent, he said, the company should assess whether to transfer plants. &nbsp;>
Mexico, by the way, stands at the window waiting to see what will happen. President Claudia Sheinbaum said that the country "has reserve plans in case tariffs enter into force. Whatever the United States has decided, Mexico is ready." And the Canda doesn't even look. "We are ready - said the Canadian Foreign Minister Melanie Joly. - with a price plan on products for 155 billion dollars, and we are ready to start with the first tranche of tariffs of 30 billion". &nbsp;
Trump, meanwhile, wrote a post about Truth dedicated to the great farmers: "Prepare to sell a huge amount of agricultural products within the United States. >The duties and duties will start on foreign products from 2 April. There will be fun!" &nbsp;
