AGI -&nbsp;Volodymyr Zelensky "would show more gratitude" to the United States. Donald&nbsp;Trump said that on Friday he clashed verbally with his Ukrainian counterpart, but underlined that the agreement on rare land offered in Kiev >a compensation for military aid received may still be concluded. "I only think it should be more grateful, because this country has been close to him in good and bad luck," he said&nbsp;Trump&nbsp; during a ceremony at the White House. The President of the United States has stated that it has not yet been said to suspend military aid to Ukraine.&nbsp;
tycoon, however, stated that he had spoken with his European counterparts on the weekend to discuss how to end the war in Ukraine. "We will make arrangements with everyone to get the end of this war, including Europe and European nations," Trump told reporters at the White House after he was asked if he was considering revoking sanctions to Russia in the event of a peace agreement. "Most of them are my friends, the heads of state, the leaders of the various countries. Four prime ministers and five presidents have called me in the last two days and want to solve the matter." &nbsp;
According to the National Security Council of the White House, Michael Waltz, the Ukrainian president " could have left with an economic guarantee that Ukraine would benefit from and, I think, the world for a generation, so we did not understand why there was so much hostility." For his part, Zelensky continues to confide in US support to reach peace with Russia. "We continue to work with partners - he wrote on X -. We have already had talks and other steps will come soon. It is very important that we try to make our diplomacy really concrete to end this war as soon as possible. We need true peace and the Ukrainians want it more than all because war spoils our cities and our countries. We lose our people. We have to stop the war and ensure security. We are working together with America and our European partners and we hope very much in the support of the United States on the path to peace. Peace is necessary as soon as possible." &nbsp;
Of Ukraine also spoke Giorgia Meloni. "I believe that in the end, beyond what may seem, the goal is a shared goal, in the end all share the same goal" which is to "take peace in Ukraine, bring in Ukraine a just peace, bring a stable, lasting peace, I would say definitive. So the central question is - said the prime minister at the 21st century, airing in the second evening on Rai 1 - how do we build a peace that foresees such security guarantees for Ukraine" and "make sure that it cannot return the war. This serves all >, serves Ukraine, serves European countries, especially those who feel rightly threatened by Russia and serves Trump&nbsp; who is a strong leader and who clearly cannot afford to sign an agreement that someone might violate tomorrow."&nbsp; On what happened to the White House last Friday the premier has his idea: ""We say that they are not debates that normally take place in front of the cameras. He didn't help." &nbsp;&nbsp;"On the proposal of sending European soldiers advanced from France and Britain - the premier explained -, Italy expressed its perplexity: In my opinion it is a very complex thing in the realization, I am not convinced of the effectiveness, it is the reason why, as you know, we said that we will not send the Italian soldiers in Ukraine.> Surely it is a time when all those who make proposals are doing something useful in trying to find a solution."
In the meantime, the media believes that the White House is planning to loosen sanctions to Russia, despite not yet reached the successful agreement to end the war in Ukraine. That's what the Guardian writes, quoting Reuters agency. Such a move by the &nbsp administration; Trump&nbsp; would reverse the aggressive position assumed by Joe Biden towards Moscow after the invasion of his neighbor in 2022. It is not clear what Trump&nbsp wants; in exchange for the loosening of sanctions, although the move is still in the planning stage. According to the sources, the White House asked the State and Treasury departments to draft a list of sanctions that could be loose, so that US officials can discuss it with Russian representatives in the coming days, in the context of the extensive talks of the Moscow administration on the improvement of diplomatic and economic relations. The sanctions offices would be drafting a proposal to revoke sanctions on certain entities and individuals, including some Russian oligarchs. It is not clear what Washington could ask in particular in exchange for any delay in sanctions.&nbsp;>

